\begin_layout Section
The Patient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rochaix1989"

\end_inset

, the patient has a utility function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U & = & u(h(t,d))
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is health, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is treatment, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is disease variable classified by its severity of illness, which belongs
 to an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the minimum level of severity and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the maximum.
 The patient has a preference over the level of treatment 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is a mix of inputs used.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a von Neumann--Morgenstern utility function, which is three times differenti
al.
 It is also assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 has both increasing and decreasing segments to capture the negative health
 effects of over-treatment.
 I also assume that increasing the level of severity increases the marginal
 utility of treatment 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{ts}>0)$
\end_inset

.
 Under perfect agency and full information the maximization problem is simply
 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\max_{t}u(h(t,d))\ F.O.C\ u_{t}h_{t}=0\label{eq:eq:full-information}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, there is a unique solution 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

 to the problem in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:eq:full-information"

\end_inset

, and the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}(s)$
\end_inset

 has a positive first derivative whit respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\partial t^{*}/\partial s>0)$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

