\begin_layout Standard
In reality however, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is never observed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is unobserved, but has a known distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(d)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a signal about 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and it is assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(s\mid d)$
\end_inset

 is known to the physician, but not to the patient, such that the physician
 can infer 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(d\mid s)$
\end_inset

; the probability distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 given 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is assumed that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $s'>s$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(d\mid s')$
\end_inset

 first order stochastically dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(d\mid s)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:-first-order-sthocastic-domination"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pi(d\mid s')$
\end_inset

 first order stochastically dominates 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(d\mid s)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(d\mid s')\le\pi(d\mid s)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
and for every non-decreasing function 
\begin_inset Formula $u:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Eu(h;\pi(d\mid s'))\ge Eu(h;\pi(d\mid s))\label{eq:D1-fosd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Static setting under full information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive the optimal behavior of the patient, I start by analyzing the
 patient optimal treatment decision 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, where the patient has the same information as the physician.
 for simplicity, I assume now that the only relevant costs are 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 produced at a cost 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c=c(s)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $c'>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c''>0$
\end_inset

.
 Given this, a rational agent would acquire a volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Eu(h-c(s);\pi(d\mid s))=Eu(h)\pi(d)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is, the expected gain in utility from a decrease in uncertainty, must
 equal the loss in utility from the cost of obtaining signals 
\begin_inset Formula $s.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dynamic analysis under full information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now given that in each period the patient observes signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and that over time, this information is aggregated into 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{i}=s+s_{i-1}+\cdots s_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 indicates the amount of signals acquired in the present period, Then I
 can write the patients utility as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Eu(h_{i}-c_{i}(s);\pi(d_{i}\mid s_{i}))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then clearly as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(d\mid s_{i})\le\pi(d\mid s_{i-1})$
\end_inset

 the amount of information optimally acquired acquired at time 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is less that the amount of information optimally acquired at time 
\begin_inset Formula $i-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Assume that the same amount for information is acquired in each period,
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}(s)=c_{i}(s)=c_{i-1}(s)$
\end_inset

.
 Then given definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:-first-order-sthocastic-domination"

\end_inset

 it must be true that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Eu(h_{i}-\bar{c}(s);\pi(d_{i}\mid s_{i}))\ge Eu(h_{i-1}-\bar{c}(s);\pi(d_{i-1}\mid s_{i-1}))\label{eq:proff-signal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
However if 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:proff-signal"

\end_inset

 holds, then it must also be true that for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Eu(h_{i}-c_{i}(s);\pi(d_{i}\mid s_{i}))=Eu(h_{i-1}-c_{i-1}(s);\pi(d_{i-1}\mid s_{i-1}))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(s)\le c_{i-1}(s)\Leftrightarrow s_{i}\ge s_{i-1}$
\end_inset

 or that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $i-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The insurance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is assumed that the cost of providing treatment 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 can be perfectly observed by the insurance, such that the price 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}=C_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 However, the cost of acquiring signals 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 (e.i.
 diagnosing the patient) 
\begin_inset Formula $C(s)$
\end_inset

 is unobserved.
 Therefore the payment for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is based on the average cost of diagnosing 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta^{*}=\int_{s}C_{i}(s)d\pi(s\mid d)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

