\begin_layout Section
The physician
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The physician has a net income of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y(t,s)=P_{t}+\delta-C_{t}-C(s)+\lambda Eu
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the revenue generated for treatment 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the per--patient, per--period fee and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t})$
\end_inset

 is the cost of treatment 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C(s)$
\end_inset

 is the cost signals 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 It is assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $C(s)$
\end_inset

 is convex in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $C_{s}'>0,C_{s}''>0$
\end_inset

).
 This captures the idea that information acquisition is more costly, the
 more information is needed, due to fact that I assume that the physician
 acquires the least costly information first.
 The last term is the weight the physician puts on patient utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Static analyzes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like the patient I assume that the physician knows 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(d)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(s\mid d)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(s)$
\end_inset

 , but that 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is unobserved.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As it is assumed that the insurance does not know 
\begin_inset Formula $C(s)$
\end_inset

, but can only infer the average cost of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(s)$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 However, after 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{*}$
\end_inset

 is determined, each physician my choose a different level of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, depending on his level of altruism 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, as the physician may acquire more or less signals than the average,
 the physician realized payment is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y(s,t)=\delta^{*}-C(s)+\lambda Eu,\text{ as }P_{t}=C_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that the physician will only treat the patient if he makes a profit,
 I define the physicians participation constraint by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta^{*}+\lambda Eu\ge C(s)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the only the patients expected utility and the physicians cost change
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, we must have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial}{\partial s}(\delta^{*}-C(s)) & =\lambda\frac{\partial Eu}{\partial s}\ \text{ and }\label{eq:max-physician}\\
\delta^{*}+\lambda Eu & \ge C(s)\label{eq:eq:constraint-physician}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:eq:constraint-physician"

\end_inset

, we know that no physician will ever acquire more signals than
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta^{*}+\lambda Eu=C(s)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming now that physicians have the same prior 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(d)$
\end_inset

, then for all physician is it true that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(d\mid s)\propto\pi(d)\pi(s\mid d)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

